(2434, 1, '2015-04-12 02:31:16', '2015-04-12 02:31:16', '<em>What is the Summer Learning Program (SLP)?</em>\r\n\r\nIts an important education initiative in Ontario. Since 2010, the Council of Ontario Directors of Education (CODE), backed with funding and support from the Literacy and Numeracy Secretariat, has coordinated the organization of Summer Learning Programs in boards across the province.\r\n\r\n<em>What is the aim of the SLP?</em>\r\n\r\nRight from the beginning, the aim has been to identify promising practices and connect boards to an in-depth research study examining the impact of summer learning  all while supporting students in the primary grades who would benefit from engaging and interactive classes in literacy, numeracy, or literacy support for First Nations, Mtis and Inuit (FNMI).\r\n\r\n<em>What has the research study discovered about the effectiveness of Summer Learning?</em>\r\n\r\nThe research findings to date clearly indicate that summer literacy and numeracy programs do make a difference by minimizing summer learning loss while increasing student confidence. As an example, pre- and post-test scores in reading show that students enrolled in literacy classes made average gains in reading of approximately five weeks in instruction time. Students enrolled in literacy/numeracy blended classes made similar gains in reading as well as average gains in mathematics of approximately seven weeks in instruction time.\r\n\r\n<em>Who can attend the summer programs?</em>\r\n\r\nBoards may invite any students currently registered in senior kindergarten, grades 1, 2 and/or 3 to participate in the program. It is suggested that preference be given to students experiencing achievement gaps and/or those who may have social and economic challenges to school achievement.\r\n\r\n<em>Can parents be involved?</em>\r\n\r\nThe involvement of parents is <span style="text-decoration: underline;">critical</span> to the success of the Summer Learning Programs. Boards are asked to communicate and engage with parents of SLP students throughout the program, and ensure they understand the purpose, expected student outcomes and logistics of the program. Parents are required to complete a survey and commit to regular attendance of their child(ren). In addition, some programs invite parents into the classroom to participate in activities.\r\n\r\n<em>How many boards offer summer learning?</em>\r\n\r\nFor the first time since the SLP began, all 73 school boards in Ontario are offering summer learning programs.\r\n\r\n<em>What about specifics: How long do the programs run, how many students per class, etc.</em>\r\n\r\nBoards organize programs with no fewer than 15 students per class. The SLP must be offered for a minimum of 3 weeks with interactive and engaging literacy or numeracy instruction scheduled daily for at least a half day or the equivalent of 45 hours of literacy or numeracy instruction.\r\n\r\n<em>What else does summer learning offer students besides literacy and numeracy classes?</em>\r\n\r\nThe SLP is expected to include a recreation component, and boards may enter into community partnerships with local not-for-profit agencies or organizations (e.g., YMCA, Boys and Girls Club, local museums). Engaging the community is an excellent way to enrich and support academic learning by integrating healthy lifestyles, drama, music and the arts into summer learning.', 'About The OSLP', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '2199-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-12 02:31:16', '2015-04-12 02:31:16', '', 2199, 'http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/2199-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2435, 1, '2015-04-12 15:00:09', '2015-04-12 15:00:09', '<strong>An important note on collecting research data (as required): </strong>Email the completed Board plan to CODE by June 30, and become familiar with the requirements of the research protocol (including parent surveys, testing of students, collecting of data and completion of the spread sheet). This may vary from year to year. Consult board policies for confidentiality guidelines and collection of data procedures, and contact research team staff as necessary for help with issues specific to the research protocol\r\n\r\nInput as much data as required into the spreadsheet in June. <em>This is critically important.</em>\r\n\r\nMuch of the material in this section is drawn from the <em>Summer Learning Program Planning Guide </em>(2014), which has been developed to support boards as they implement summer programs. In addition, a number of summer learning resources have been developed by boards and are available on this website.', 'Development and Implementation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '66-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-12 15:00:09', '2015-04-12 15:00:09', '', 66, 'http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/66-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
