earning Programs. Boards are asked to communicate and engage with parents of SLP students throughout the program, and ensure they understand the purpose, expected student outcomes and logistics of the program. Parents are required to complete a survey and commit to regular attendance of their child(ren). In addition, most programs invite parents into the classroom to participate in activities, and learn how to continue supporting their child''s learning at home.\r\n<h3>How many boards offer summer learning?</h3>\r\nFor the first time since the SLP began, all 72 school boards and two school authorities in Ontario are offering summer learning programs.\r\n<h3>What about specifics: How long do the programs run, how many students per class, etc.</h3>\r\nBoards organize programs with no fewer than 15 students per class. The SLP must be offered for a minimum of 3 weeks with interactive and engaging literacy or numeracy instruction scheduled daily for at least a half day or the equivalent of 45 hours of literacy or numeracy instruction.\r\n<h3>What else does summer learning offer students besides literacy and numeracy classes?</h3>\r\nThe SLP is expected to include a recreation component, and boards may enter into community partnerships with local not-for-profit agencies or organizations (e.g., YMCA, Boys and Girls Club, local museums). Engaging the community is an excellent way to enrich and support academic learning by integrating healthy lifestyles, drama, music and the arts into summer learning.\r\n\r\nTo learn more about summer learning, please see <a title="links to SLP reports" href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/faq/forms-and-documents/">SLP reports</a> from previous years.', 'About The SLP', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2199-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-08 21:21:26', '2015-05-08 21:21:26', '', 2199, 'http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/2199-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(2544, 3, '2015-05-08 21:29:50', '2015-05-08 21:29:50', 'Since 2010, the summer learning program and its research protocol have had the same objective: to benefit students and reduce summer literacy and numeracy learning losses. As these reports attest, the research protocol is developing important data needed for strong evidenced-based policy making, and the further enhancement of high-quality summer programs in Ontario. The comments, ideas, strategies and successes gathered here from the SLP community have helped summer learning in Ontario make a greater impact on more students.\r\n<h3>SLP Reports</h3>\r\nThe following Report has been prepared by the Literacy and Numeracy Secretariat to outline the impact of the 2014 Summer Learning Program in minimizing summer learning loss.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Summer-Learning-Final-Report-March-23-2015.docx" target="_blank">Summer Learning Program Report 2014: Program Monitoring for Accountability</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SummerLearning_2013_Report.pdf">SummerLearning_2013_Report</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SLLP-report-2012.pdf">SLLP report 2012</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SLLP-report-2011.pdf">SLLP report 2011</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Summer-Literacy-Learning_technical-appendix-2011.pdf">Summer Literacy Learning_technical appendix 2011</a>\r\n<h3>SLP planning guide</h3>\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SLLP-Planning-Guide-2014-English_HR.pdf">SLLP Planning Guide 2014 English_HR</a>\r\n<h3>Research Reports</h3>\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Quantitative-and-Qualitative-Research-Results_2013.pdf">Quantitative and Qualitative Research Results_2013</a>\r\n<h3>En franais</h3>\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Le-rapport-de-2013.pdf">Le rapport de 2013</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Le-rapport-de-2012.pdf">Le rapport de 2012</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Le-rapport-de-2011.pdf">Le rapport de 2011</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Annexe-technique-du-projet-dt-de-littratie-2011.pdf">Annexe technique du projet dt de littratie 2011</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/SLLP-Planning-Guide-2014-French_D2.pdf">SLLP Planning Guide 2014 French_D2</a>\r\n\r\n<a href="http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/Rsultats-qualitatifs-et-quantitatifs-de-la-recherche_2013.pdf">Rsultats qualitatifs et quantitatifs de la recherche_2013</a>\r\n\r\ntude longitudinale de trois conseils scolaires de langue franaise, 2014\r\nL''universit d''Ottawa a complt son rapport sur les trois conseils scolaires de langue franaise participant  une tude longitudinale pour dterminer si les programmes d''t de littratie font une diffrence dans le temps. Le rapport complet est disponible seulement en franais. Chaque conseil a reu son propre rapport individuel.', 'Summer Learning Reports', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2195-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-05-08 21:29:50', '2015-05-08 21:29:50', '', 2195, 'http://staging.ontariosummerlearning.org/2195-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
